\begin_layout Section
Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Key work in this area comes from Ireland 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

and Frank 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankModel"

\end_inset

.
 Heffetz (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PalgraveDictEcon2006,heffetz_visibility,CharlesHurstRace"

\end_inset

) builds a visibility index - while using the model proposed by Ireland
 where an exogenous signal visibility 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is modeled as the signaling factor that causes a consumer to deviate from
 the optimal choice he would have made in the absence of signaling (visibility).
 This 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

private
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(v,w)$
\end_inset

 is then considered for a two-commodity world that comprises of a visible
 product
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and an invisible product
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 (whose quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 are consumed respectively).
 The utility function in presence of signal
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 can be represented as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U & =F(f(v,w),s)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This utility function is assumed to hold for all individuals and reflects
 all demand characteristics as well as spectators’ inference about status.
 The signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 itself is represented in terms of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spectator inference function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 -
\begin_inset Formula $g(v)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
s & =f(v,g(v))
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the convexity assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $U=(1-a)\cdot f(v,w)+a\cdot f(v,g(v))$
\end_inset

 (for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<a<1$
\end_inset

), a given budget constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $w+pv=y$
\end_inset

 and an inference function 
\begin_inset Formula $h(v)=g(v)+pv$
\end_inset

, the conditions for a signaling equilibrium are derived for a Cobb-Douglas
 utility function (used by Heffetz).
 The solution (and the calibration which we seek) largely depends on the
 choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\cdot,\cdot)$
\end_inset

.
 With the quasi-linear or homothetic choices, the equilibrium conditions
 result in significant deviation from private utility maximization in the
 low-income group
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

