\begin_layout Subsection
Separability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Separability and additivity are usual assumption in aggregation of commodities.
 Whether a category of visual consumption can be considered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

separable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or for utility maximisation or not - remains to be tested in the study.
 At this point, only a comparison of visible vs invisible products is being
 considered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
While considering separability of aggregates, one lumps commodities whose
 prices move together.
 For example, if prices of two commodities A (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{A}$
\end_inset

) and B (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{B}$
\end_inset

) are inversely correlated, then grouping them is equivalent to observing
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{A}+q_{B})$
\end_inset

 for the aggregate price 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{p_{A}q_{A}+p_{B}q_{B}}}{q_{A}+q_{B}}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{A}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{B}$
\end_inset

varying in opposite directions may i) change aggregate price significantly
 and ii) cause consumer to change 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{B}$
\end_inset

 in a way not captured by the model.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally, if one can recover systematic price variations (regional, seasonal,
 product-differentiation-related, quality-related differences), it is possible
 to obtain reliable estimates of price elasticities from cross-sectional
 data.
 However, a simple aggregation is fraught with problems as consumers choose
 quality as well as quantity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChungCrossSec"

\end_inset

.
 Quality-adjusted price elasticities would this need to be further explored
 in the study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Geographical variations are meant to be analyzed in the survey as well.
 In his study of Cote d'Ivoire, Deaton notes that purchases may not give
 an accurate picture of the consumption since a lot of consumption in the
 country (e.g.
 meat) is produced within the household (a problem particularly significant
 when notes zero purchases are noted for a significant portion of the data).
 Such differences because of geographic and income are handled by identifying
 clusters based on geography.
 The parameters provided by regressions run within the cluster, follow the
 regression on the overall data
